  "prompt": "How can an international company (not registered in France) hire French Nationals based out of France as freelancers or for fixed term contract?",
  "response": "There are several ways an international company can hire French nationals based in France:\n\n1. Direct Freelance Contracting\n- Use platforms like Upwork, Freelancer, or local French freelance platforms\n- Establish a clear independent contractor agreement\n- Ensure compliance with French labor laws\n- Freelancer responsible for own taxes and social contributions\n\n2. Professional Services Agreement\n- Create a B2B service contract with the individual's micro-enterprise (micro-entrepreneur)\n- Freelancer must be registered as a micro-entrepreneur in France\n- Simpler administrative process\n- Freelancer handles own tax and social charges\n\n3. Temporary Employment Agencies (Portage Salarial)\n- Use an umbrella company that legally employs the worker\n- Handles payroll, taxes, and social contributions\n- Provides legal framework for short-term or project-based work\n- Slightly higher administrative costs\n\n4. Local Subsidiary or Branch Office\n- Establish a legal entity in France\n- Most complex but provides full employment capabilities\n- Ensures full compliance with French labor regulations\n\n5. Professional Employer Organization (PEO)\n- Outsource employment administration\n- PEO manages payroll, benefits, compliance\n- Reduces administrative burden\n- Typically more expensive\n\nKey Considerations:\n- Comply with French labor laws\n- Understand tax obligations\n- Consider social security contributions\n- Verify worker classification\n\nRecommended steps:\n- Consult local legal and tax experts\n- Review specific contract requirements\n- Ensure proper worker classification",
